social_posts.post_text: 5 years ago today a massive wildfire burnt my house, property and neighborhood to the ground. While there is really no way to describe the devastation and loss - especially the grief over loosing my dogs - I can also say that in the aftermath there were moments of real beauty and true connection. I feel so fortunate to have experienced the incredible resilience of my neighbors, the kindness and support of friends, clients and strangers alike. And, 5 years later I am happy to say that the experience, while devastating has also shaped me into a different human and for that I am grateful. #thomasfire #michaelaboehm

Join us for this special retreat exclusively for members of our study group programs, past and present. ​​​​​​​​

Revitalize and deepen your existing practices while receiving transmission and instruction in new lineage methods, in ways that are only possible in person. ​​​​​​​​

​​​​​​​​
Located at Portugal's Southwest Atlantic Coast, this isolated evergreen valley creates an abundant oasis where two creeks come together to nourish an ancient lush forest and wildlife vistas, surrounding us with clear water, abundant sunlight, green vibrant plant life, a fire pit and an amazing night sky.​​​​​​​​

This retreat is exclusively open to members of our study group programs, past and present. If you have participated in any year of the study groups, you may register without completing an application. ​​​​​​​​

⁣
Join us in January and learn how to lead your own Wild Woman’s Circle™ so you can bring this timely work to the women of your community.⁣ ✨

⁣
The Wild Woman’s Circle™ uses potent embodiment practices, women’s group exercises, and sacred rituals originally conceived for my own women’s circles. ⁣
⁣
The material is designed to provide you with a transformational immersion into this body of work, as both participant and teacher.⁣
Our live online training offers new in-depth experiential engagement and enables you to teach, either freestanding (as a weekly or monthly circle) or as an adjunct to other modalities.⁣

Why is it that many of us break New Years (or any other...) resolutions so quickly?​​​​​​​​
​​​​​​​​
There are actually many factors that work against us when we want to change patterns and habits.​​​​​​​​
​​​​​​​​
1. Energy Conservation/Optimization: Our body/brain does not want to use up extra energy and bandwidth to re-create a pattern we have already "installed" through previous learning.​​​​​​​​
​​​​​​​​
2. Survival: What we have already "successfully" survived as a behavior is safer than a new "unproven - therefore potentially deadly" pattern.​​​​​​​​
​​​​​​​​
3. The desired - or aspired - behavior change does not align with deeper motivation of heart and body. Just because something is thought of as a good idea does not mean our body-mind is on board. ​​​​​​​​
​​​​​​​​
4. Unrealistic goals. This includes excessive time commitments, changes for which additional skill development is required, aspirational desires which don't match your lifestyle and too many changes at once.​​​​​​​​
​​​​​​​​
5. A rebellious streak. Sometimes we still live out some early-in-life rebellion which served us well when we formed who we are now...but when wanting to optimize patterns as adults those beliefs are actively holding us back.​​​​​​​​
​​​​​​​​
6. Disconnection from natural patterns and rhythms. The middle of winter might not be the best time for your body to do a cold juice cleanse. Dark mornings might not be conducive to early morning walks, etc....​​​​​​​​
​​​​​​​​
And this is by no means a complete list...​​​​​​​​
So, how do we create sustainable pattern and behavior change? One often overlooked aspect is our body. While the mind can change quickly and our emotions can align with what is desired easily, our body needs to change via skill development and repetition to acquire new habits.​​​​​​​​
​​​​​​​​
Last week I gave a free talk about embodied change in which I go into specific details and give free resources. You can find the link in my bio.

Yesterday would have been my grandmother’s 117th Birthday.
Born in pre-first world war Vienna, she came from a line of talented artists. She was unconventional, creative, opinionated and incredibly generous. When I lived in Vienna, there were always people at her house, playing cards, making music, discussing various books and eating an unending amount of delicious food. She had a huge influence on me, from her attention to beauty to her love of animals and plants, from the way she prepared food to her stubborn perseverance.
When she was in her late 70‘s she suffered a stroke, which left her partly paralyzed and unable to speak clearly. I moved in with her to offer assistance. But, to her being restricted in her life was simply unacceptable as it inconvenienced her social schedule. So, she‘d spent considerable hours each day walking up and down the corridor with her walker and reading aloud until late at night. It took a year till she had fully recovered, but she did and lived for another 10+ years with vigor and enjoyment. I have huge gratitude for her and who she was - a role model for making strong, independent choices, not conforming to convention while also having to sacrifice some aspects of her aspirations to give my father the upbringing he had despite his father dying young. I‘ve been thinking about her a lot in the context of familial imprints and positive female role models…and feel very lucky to have had so many incredible times with her.

⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⁣

⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⁣

⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⁣

⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⁣
The method is specifically designed as a “no force/no imposition “ somatic modality and can be practiced by anyone, regardless of physical health, ability, fitness level or age. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⁣
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⁣

The Lady of Contentment Surveys Her Land

There comes a moment in any woman's life where she realizes that there are choices to be made. Things will have gone wrong, there will have been losses, betrayal and grief. 

Out of these experiences she can choose to be bitter and withdrawn, or she can focus on what is good and right. 

The Lady of Contentment is an invitation to choose goodness, regardless of where you are on your path. You can look out over the landscape of your existence and see the beauty, the learning and the joy, or you can turn inwards and contract over those losses. 

Look at her body and feel how relaxed softness allows her to be appreciated, how each line on her face tells a story, how she is adorned as an expression of who she truly is - an offering of beauty for herself and those who see her. 

She is the place of inner and outer contentment, neither contracted and withdrawn nor overly in your face or demanding attention. Hers is the message of the middle path, not out of convention, cowardice or resignation, but out of the knowledge that she is walking the razor's edge of opposing forces, with a relaxed open heart.
